        <h2>RNA processing and splicing in the brain</h2>
        
        <p>A core focus is how genes are spliced in the brain, how inaccuracies in this process accumulate with age, and how they contribute to disease. We have shown that splicing accuracy varies systematically across tissues, individuals, and disease states. We build tools and databases to support this work. This includes IntroVerse (a catalogue of introns across human tissues), ggtranscript (an R package for visualising transcript isoforms), and PSQAN (a pipeline for prioritising novel transcripts from long-read RNA sequencing). We have also demonstrated that human gene annotation remains substantially incomplete in the brain, with direct consequences for interpreting neurological disease loci, including the GBA1 locus, the most important genetic risk factor for Parkinson's disease, whose transcript structure we resolved using long-read sequencing.</p>

