        <h2>Genetic regulation of brain gene expression</h2>
        <p>We use eQTL analyses to map how common genetic variants influence gene expression and splicing in specific brain regions and cell types. This work has shown that regulatory variants enriched in the basal ganglia are disproportionately relevant to neurological and psychiatric disease risk, and that genetic regulation operates at the level of both nuclear and cytoplasmic RNA compartments.</p>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <i>Regulatory sites for splicing in human basal ganglia are enriched for disease-relevant information</i>
                <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-020-14483-x"
                   title="Read 'Regulatory sites for splicing in human basal ganglia are enriched for disease-relevant information'" target="_blank">
                    doi: 10.1038/s41467-020-14483-x.
                </a> Nat Commun. 2020 Feb 25;11(1):1041.
            </li>
            <li>
                <i>Analysis of subcellular RNA fractions demonstrates significant genetic regulation of gene expression in human brain post-transcriptionally</i>
                <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-023-40324-0"
                   title="Read 'Analysis of subcellular RNA fractions demonstrates significant genetic regulation of gene expression in human brain post-transcriptionally'" target="_blank">
                    doi: 10.1038/s41598-023-40324-0.
                </a> Sci Rep. 2023 Aug 24;13(1):13874.
            </li>
        </ul>

        

        <h2>Mapping the living human brain</h2>
        <p>In a major multidisciplinary project, we are building a molecular map of the living human brain by integrating quantitative MRI with transcriptomic data, enabling biological interpretation of neuroimaging signals in health and disease.</p>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <i>A molecular map of the living human brain from quantitative MRI</i>
                <a href="https://doi.org/10.1101/2025.09.24.678316"
                   title="Read 'A molecular map of the living human brain from quantitative MRI'" target="_blank">
                    doi: 10.1101/2025.09.24.678316.
                </a> bioRxiv. 2025.
            </li>
        </ul>


        <h2>Rare neurogenetic disorders</h2>
        <p>We apply functional genomics to improve diagnostic yields in rare neurological diseases. In hereditary ataxia, integrating transcriptomic data with variant interpretation substantially increases the rate of molecular diagnosis. We also contributed to the discovery of a deep intronic FGF14 GAA repeat expansion as a cause of late-onset cerebellar ataxia, and have studied the shared neurobiology between dystonia and psychiatric disorders.</p>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <i>Functional genomics provide key insights to improve the diagnostic yield of hereditary ataxia</i>
                <a href="https://doi.org/10.1093/brain/awad009"
                   title="Read 'Functional genomics provide key insights to improve the diagnostic yield of hereditary ataxia'" target="_blank">
                    doi: 10.1093/brain/awad009.
                </a> Brain. 2023 Jul 3;146(7):2869-2884.
            </li>
            <li>
